"What Dr. Shurney Taught Me" follows the journey through different events this sickle cell warrior may have experienced living with sickle cell disease. The goal of the book is to raise awareness of sickle cell disease and give friends and family a better understanding of what someone afflicted may endure in their lifetime.

To discover more amazing speakers and creators like La' Shardae Scott and Eric Scott, check out our SickleCellCon playlists on YouTube!

node.text:
My parents traveled a far distance to get a diagnosis for my swollen hands and the pain in my joints. We didn’t have access to a test to determine my genetic status. When they found out I had sickle cell disease at 6 months, they were devastated because they were told no cure was available in Kenya. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The Kenyan government and healthcare system is not built for people living with sickle cell disease. There isn’t insurance to support the care you need, so we have to pay out-of-pocket for expenses associated with sickle cell. There aren’t many specialists or education and awareness around sickle cell, so many of us are reliant on advocacy groups.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
When I’m in severe pain, I have to bargain with the doctor to receive strong pain medications. That is when I get paracetamol (Tylenol) through IV, when I’m in the hospital. If I’m in mild pain at home I get massages from my parents and sister and we get labs done to find out what's happening. This is how I manage sickle cell pain at home. But on a day-to-day basis, the best way I know how to manage sickle cell disease is by eating a proper diet, staying warm, avoiding exertion and most importantly, listening to my body.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Growing up and even today symptoms I experience are having yellow eyes and delayed growth. I notice that I'm not growing normally like other guys and I’d say one of the hardest parts about living with sickle cell disease is not being able to...⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Read more about Victor's experience in managing sickle cell disease in Kenya and how he remains positive. Link in bio.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
#sicklecell101 #sicklecell #SCDToolbox #sicklecellawarenessmonth ⁠#sc101fosc⁠⁠

node.text:
💊vs🌿 Imagine pitting one treatment option against another?  It doesn't make sense when sickle cell is such a beast and we have such limited options.⁠
⁠
To me it is never pharmacologicals against whole foods... I utilize all! I take my hydroxyurea with a green kale smoothie while scheduling my next follow up appointment because I need all the help I can get to tackle this COMPLEX (MULTI-ORGAN) GENETIC DISEASE and live my life the way I want to live it. ⁠
⁠
There is not one way to manage sickle cell... You're not going to be a healthy person if you take a drug therapy for SCD, but you're not eating healthy or looking after your mental health. ⁠
⁠
We need drug therapies, tribes, alternative therapies, mental wellbeing, advocacy, nutrition, healthcare, exercise, education and faith to manage sickle cell disease. Each has a very specific target and only utilizing one of these options is simply not enough.⁠
⁠
My message to my fellow warriors is to utilize all the options we have to live your best life with sickle cell disease
⁠
– Cass (@casmopolitan)⁠
⁠
#sicklecell101 #sicklecell #SCDTools #sicklecellawareness #sicklecellawarenessmonth

node.text:
"Growing up I didn’t know I had sickle cell disease until I was 19, after the birth of my son. I grew up in a time where nobody knew what specifically was wrong. My grandmother treated my excruciating pain episodes with applying heat, massaging me, and having me rest. That was it!  I got no narcotics or anything like that. So I would just hurt until my pain went away.⁠
⁠
Back then, the knowledge base of sickle cell disease was limited, but fortunately for me, my OBGYN was an African American doctor, who studied at a HBCU in the south. So he was ahead of his time and informed about what to do for sickle cell disease – he even diagnosed me.⁠
⁠
After I was diagnosed with sickle cell disease my options were limited. I had access to a comprehensive sickle cell center, where I was treated by people that knew something about sickle cell, but for the most part, treatment was only managing the pain when I had a serious pain crisis. Not even blood transfusions were an option or offered. I hadn’t started receiving blood transfusions until my 50s. You know a lot of us with sickle cell disease don't have really great veins, so getting a needle in a line was not easy. When I started getting transfused regularly it was suggested that I get a permanent line put in, and I was like, “Oh no I ain’t trying to do that. I don't want to do that.” It was at this moment, hydroxyurea was offered to me as an alternative to getting a permanent line. I was 55 or 60 years old.⁠
⁠
And you know, one of the side effects of hydroxyurea is losing your hair... "⁠
⁠
Read more about Wanda's experience with #hydroxyurea. Link in bio and stories.⁠
⁠

Here's to us! 🥂 September is our month to celebrate our accomplishments, remember our loved ones who gained their wings, and to educate and raise awareness to those around us about sickle cell. ⁠
⁠
Happy Sickle Cell Awareness Month!! 🎉⁠
⁠
This month we listened to you all and created a campaign we hope you will find useful in helping you manage sickle cell disease. It's called Tools in the SCD Toolbox: Treatment Options for Sickle Cell Disease.⁠
⁠
We are breaking down global treatment options available for us and sharing the benefits of each treatment option. ⁠
⁠
We also want to hear from you. How do you manage your #sicklecell disease? ⁠
⁠
Please share the message far and wide that September is Sickle Cell Awareness month, and stay tuned for what we have for you all. We're excited to bring this information to the community in hopes to have an ever better informed community and for you to know what options are available to manage sickle cell disease. ⁠
⁠
#sicklecell101 #sicklecellawarenessmonth #NSCAM21

node.text:
We at #SickleCell101 are collaborating with Klein Buendel to identify teens who can help with the development of Pinpoint, an app that helps young sickle cell patients assess and talk about their pain with their parents and healthcare providers.

To see if you are eligible to participate, visit scdstudies.com/featured/pinpoint (link in bio) to learn more PINPOINT and help contribute to research for sickle cell. Don’t forget to also share this with any other individuals who can also participate in this survey.

More about this study

Pain, which is the hallmark symptom of sickle cell disease (SCD), is also the most common clinical problem associated with SCD-related hospital admissions in children living with sickle cell disease.
Yet programs to assist children and adolescents with better identification and communication of their pain are lacking. 

Pinpoint is a phone and tablet app that uses interactive games to help teens learn how to communicate their sickle cell disease. Research shows that interactive gaming technology can enhance adolescents' learning and can be especially effective in delivering health-related messages and tools to improve self-care. The goal of this study is to develop a final, effective version of the Pinpoint app. We are looking for teens, ages 13-17 years old to participate in this virtual research study and assist with the development of Pinpoint. This project is approved by the Western Institutional Review Board and funded by the National Institute on Minority Health & Health Disparities, a part of the National Institutes of Health (Grant Number: R44 MD010746). 

Visit our patient-friendly research platform, Sickle Cell Studies to learn more about the Pinpoint Study and help contribute to research for sickle cell.
